# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: particle-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In modern physics, **antimatter** is defined as matter composed of the antiparticles (or "partners") of the corresponding particles in "ordinary" matter, and can be thought of as matter with reversed charges and parity, or going backward in time (see CPT symmetry).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antimatter occurs in natural processes like cosmic ray collisions and some types of radioactive decay.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antiparticles can also be generated at particle accelerators, but only a tiny fraction of these have successfully been bound together in experiments to form antiatoms.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Total artificial production has been only a few nanograms.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] No macroscopic amount of antimatter has ever been assembled due to the extreme cost and difficulty of production and handling.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Nonetheless, antimatter is an essential component of widely available applications related to beta decay, such as positron emission tomography, radiation therapy, and industrial imaging.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In theory, a particle and its antiparticle (for example, a proton and an antiproton) have the same mass, but opposite electric charge, and other differences in quantum numbers.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] A collision between any particle and its anti-particle partner leads to their mutual annihilation, giving rise to different proportions of intense photons (gamma rays), neutrinos, and sometimes less-massive particle–antiparticle pairs.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The majority of the total energy of annihilation emerges in the form of ionizing radiation.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] If surrounding matter is present, the energy content of this radiation will be absorbed and converted into other forms of energy, such as heat or light.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The amount of energy released is usually proportional to the total mass of the collided matter and antimatter, in accordance with the mass–energy equivalence equation, *E*=*mc*2.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antiparticles bind with each other to form antimatter, just as ordinary particles bind to form normal matter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] For example, a positron (the antiparticle of the electron) and an antiproton (the antiparticle of the proton) can form an antihydrogen atom.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The nuclei of antihelium have been artificially produced, albeit with difficulty, and are the most complex anti-nuclei so far observed.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Physical principles indicate that complex antimatter atomic nuclei are possible, as well as anti-atoms corresponding to the known chemical elements.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] There is strong evidence that the observable universe is composed almost entirely of ordinary matter, as opposed to an equal mixture of matter and antimatter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This asymmetry of matter and antimatter in the visible universe is one of the great unsolved problems in physics.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The process by which this inequality between matter and antimatter particles is hypothesised to have occurred is called baryogenesis.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antimatter particles carry the same charge as matter particles, but of opposite sign.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] That is, an antiproton is negatively charged and an antielectron (positron) is positively charged.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Neutrons do not carry a net charge, but their constituent quarks do.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Protons and neutrons have a baryon number of +1, while antiprotons and antineutrons have a baryon number of –1.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Similarly, electrons have a lepton number of +1, while that of positrons is –1.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] When a particle and its corresponding antiparticle collide, they are both converted into energy.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The French term for "made of or pertaining to antimatter", *contraterrene*, led to the initialism "C.T." and the science fiction term *seetee*, as used in such novels as *Seetee Ship*.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The idea of negative matter appears in past theories of matter that have now been abandoned.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Using the once popular vortex theory of gravity, the possibility of matter with negative gravity was discussed by William Hicks in the 1880s.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Between the 1880s and the 1890s, Karl Pearson proposed the existence of "squirts" and sinks of the flow of aether.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The squirts represented normal matter and the sinks represented negative matter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Pearson's theory required a fourth dimension for the aether to flow from and into.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The term antimatter was first used by Arthur Schuster in two rather whimsical letters to *Nature* in 1898, in which he coined the term.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] He hypothesized antiatoms, as well as whole antimatter solar systems, and discussed the possibility of matter and antimatter annihilating each other.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Schuster's ideas were not a serious theoretical proposal, merely speculation, and like the previous ideas, differed from the modern concept of antimatter in that it possessed negative gravity.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The modern theory of antimatter began in 1928, with a paper by Paul Dirac.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Dirac realised that his relativistic version of the Schrödinger wave equation for electrons predicted the possibility of antielectrons.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Although Dirac had laid the groundwork for the existence of these "antielectrons" he initially failed to pick up on the implications contained within his own equation.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] He freely gave the credit for that insight to J.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Robert Oppenheimer, whose seminal paper "On the Theory of Electrons and Protons" (Feb 14th 1930) drew on Dirac's equation and argued for the existence of a positively charged electron (a positron), which as a counterpart to the electron should have the same mass as the electron itself.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This meant that it could not be, as Dirac had in fact suggested, a proton.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Dirac further postulated the existence of antimatter in a 1931 paper which referred to the positron as an "anti-electron".
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Anderson in 1932 and named positrons from "positive electron".
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Although Dirac did not himself use the term antimatter, its use follows on naturally enough from antielectrons, antiprotons, etc.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The Feynman–Stueckelberg interpretation states that antiparticles obey the same equations of motion as regular particles but with charge, parity and time inverted.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This allows analysis of antiparticles using Feynman diagrams with time reversed.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] After Carl Anderson's discovery of the positron in 1932, it was 22 years before the next antimatter particle was found.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In 1955 Chamberlain, Segrè, Wiegand, Ypsilantis publish their the discovery of the antiproton and in 1956 Cork, Lambertson, Piccioni, Wenzel discovered the antineutron.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Both teams used the Bevatron in Berkeley, California.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The discovery of antimatter led to both scientific and science fiction speculations on astronomical antimatter bodies: **antiplanets**, antistars, and **antigalaxies**.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Leon Lederman at Columbia University even speculated anti-planets might harbor intelligent life.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The antigalaxy idea was also used to explain the baryon asymmetry problem: the particle physics of the Big Bang model cannot explain why our universe has more matter than antimatter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Maurice Goldhaber suggested that our universe consists of matter rather than antimatter because the one universe of each type split at the beginning of time.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] By the 1970s the asymmetry problem was accepted as unexplained and the possibility of antigalaxies largely abandoned.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] One way to denote an antiparticle is by adding a bar over the particle's symbol.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] For example, the proton and antiproton are denoted as p and p, respectively.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The same rule applies if one were to address a particle by its constituent components.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] A proton is made up of u u d quarks, so an antiproton must therefore be formed from u u d antiquarks.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Another convention is to distinguish particles by positive and negative electric charge.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Thus, the electron and positron are denoted simply as e− and e+ respectively.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] To prevent confusion, however, the two conventions are never mixed.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] There is no difference in the gravitational behavior of matter and antimatter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In other words, antimatter falls down when dropped, not up.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This was confirmed with the thin, very cold gas of thousands of antihydrogen atoms that were confined in a vertical shaft surrounded by superconducting electromagnetic coils.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] These can create a magnetic bottle to keep the antimatter from coming into contact with matter and annihilating.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The researchers then gradually weakened the magnetic fields and detected the antiatoms using two sensors as they escaped and annihilated.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Most of the anti-atoms came out of the bottom opening, and only one-quarter out of the top.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] There are compelling theoretical reasons to believe that, aside from the fact that antiparticles have different signs on all charges (such as electric and baryon charges), matter and antimatter have exactly the same properties.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This means a particle and its corresponding antiparticle must have identical masses and decay lifetimes (if unstable).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] It also implies that, for example, a star made up of antimatter (an "antistar") will shine just like an ordinary star.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This idea was tested experimentally in 2016 by the ALPHA experiment, which measured the transition between the two lowest energy states of antihydrogen.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The results, which are identical to that of hydrogen, confirmed the validity of quantum mechanics for antimatter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Most things observable from the Earth seem to be made of matter rather than antimatter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] If antimatter-dominated regions of space existed, the gamma rays produced in annihilation reactions along the boundary between matter and antimatter regions would be detectable.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antiparticles are created everywhere in the universe where high-energy particle collisions take place.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] High-energy cosmic rays striking Earth's atmosphere (or any other matter in the Solar System) produce minute quantities of antiparticles in the resulting particle jets, which are immediately annihilated by contact with nearby matter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] They may similarly be produced in regions like the center of the Milky Way and other galaxies, where very energetic celestial events occur (principally the interaction of relativistic jets with the interstellar medium).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The presence of the resulting antimatter is detectable by the two gamma rays produced every time positrons annihilate with nearby matter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The frequency and wavelength of the gamma rays indicate that each carries 511 keV of energy (that is, the rest mass of an electron multiplied by *c*2).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Observations by the European Space Agency's INTEGRAL satellite may explain the origin of a giant antimatter cloud surrounding the Galactic Center.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The observations show that the cloud is asymmetrical and matches the pattern of X-ray binaries (binary star systems containing black holes or neutron stars), mostly on one side of the Galactic Center.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] While the mechanism is not fully understood, it is likely to involve the production of electron–positron pairs, as ordinary matter gains kinetic energy while falling into a stellar remnant.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antimatter may exist in relatively large amounts in far-away galaxies due to cosmic inflation in the primordial time of the universe.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antimatter galaxies, if they exist, are expected to have the same chemistry and absorption and emission spectra as normal-matter galaxies, and their astronomical objects would be observationally identical, making them difficult to distinguish.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] NASA is trying to determine if such galaxies exist by looking for X-ray and gamma ray signatures of annihilation events in colliding superclusters.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In October 2017, scientists working on the BASE experiment at CERN reported a measurement of the antiproton magnetic moment to a precision of 1.5 parts per billion.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] It is consistent with the most precise measurement of the proton magnetic moment (also made by BASE in 2014), which supports the hypothesis of CPT symmetry.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This measurement represents the first time that a property of antimatter is known more precisely than the equivalent property in matter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antimatter quantum interferometry has been first demonstrated in 2018 in the Positron Laboratory (L-NESS) of Rafael Ferragut in Como (Italy), by a group led by Marco Giammarchi.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Positrons are produced naturally in β+ decays of naturally occurring radioactive isotopes (for example, potassium-40) and in interactions of gamma quanta (emitted by radioactive nuclei) with matter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antineutrinos are another kind of antiparticle created by natural radioactivity (β− decay).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Many different kinds of antiparticles are also produced by (and contained in) cosmic rays.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In January 2011, research by the American Astronomical Society discovered antimatter (positrons) originating above thunderstorm clouds; positrons are produced in terrestrial gamma ray flashes created by electrons accelerated by strong electric fields in the clouds.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antiprotons have also been found to exist in the Van Allen Belts around the Earth by the PAMELA module, and similar antiproton belts may exist around Jupiter, Saturn, Neptune, and Uranus.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antiparticles are also produced in any environment with a sufficiently high temperature (mean particle energy greater than the pair production threshold).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] It is hypothesized that during the period of baryogenesis, when the universe was extremely hot and dense, matter and antimatter were continually produced and annihilated.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The presence of remaining matter, and absence of detectable remaining antimatter, is called baryon asymmetry.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The exact mechanism that produced this asymmetry during baryogenesis remains an unsolved problem.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] One of the necessary conditions for this asymmetry is the violation of CP symmetry, which has been experimentally observed in the weak interaction.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Recent observations indicate black holes and neutron stars produce vast amounts of positron-electron plasma via the jets.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Satellite experiments have found evidence of positrons and a few antiprotons in primary cosmic rays, amounting to less than 1% of the particles in primary cosmic rays.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This antimatter cannot all have been created in the Big Bang, but is instead attributed to have been produced by cyclic processes at high energies.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] For instance, electron-positron pairs may be formed in pulsars, as a magnetized neutron star rotation cycle shears electron-positron pairs from the star surface.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Therein the antimatter forms a wind that crashes upon the ejecta of the progenitor supernovae.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Preliminary results from the presently operating Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer (*AMS-02*) on board the International Space Station show that positrons in the cosmic rays arrive with no directionality, and with energies that range from 10 GeV to 250 GeV.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In September, 2014, new results with almost twice as much data were presented in a talk at CERN and published in Physical Review Letters.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] A new measurement of positron fraction up to 500 GeV was reported, showing that positron fraction peaks at a maximum of about 16% of total electron+positron events, around an energy of 275 ± 32 GeV.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] At higher energies, up to 500 GeV, the ratio of positrons to electrons begins to fall again.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The absolute flux of positrons also begins to fall before 500 GeV, but peaks at energies far higher than electron energies, which peak about 10 GeV.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] These results on interpretation have been suggested to be due to positron production in annihilation events of massive dark matter particles.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Cosmic ray antiprotons also have a much higher energy than their normal-matter counterparts (protons).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] They arrive at Earth with a characteristic energy maximum of 2 GeV, indicating their production in a fundamentally different process from cosmic ray protons, which on average have only one-sixth of the energy.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] There is an ongoing search for larger antimatter nuclei, such as antihelium nuclei (that is, anti-alpha particles), in cosmic rays.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The detection of natural antihelium could imply the existence of large antimatter structures such as an antistar.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] A prototype of the *AMS-02* designated *AMS-01*, was flown into space aboard the Space Shuttle *Discovery* on STS-91 in June 1998.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] By not detecting any antihelium at all, the *AMS-01* established an upper limit of 1.1×10−6 for the antihelium to helium flux ratio.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] AMS-02 revealed in December 2016 that it had discovered a few signals consistent with antihelium nuclei amidst several billion helium nuclei.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The result remains to be verified, and as of 2017, the team is trying to rule out contamination.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Positrons were reported in November 2008 to have been generated by Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in large numbers.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] A laser drove electrons through a gold target's nuclei, which caused the incoming electrons to emit energy quanta that decayed into both matter and antimatter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Positrons were detected at a higher rate and in greater density than ever previously detected in a laboratory.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Previous experiments made smaller quantities of positrons using lasers and paper-thin targets; newer simulations showed that short bursts of ultra-intense lasers and millimeter-thick gold are a far more effective source.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In 2023, the production of the first electron-positron beam-plasma was reported by a collaboration led by researchers at University of Oxford working with the High-Radiation to Materials (HRMT) facility at CERN.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The beam demonstrated the highest positron yield achieved so far in a laboratory setting.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The experiment employed the 440 GeV proton beam, with $3\times 10^{11}$ protons, from the Super Proton Synchrotron, and irradiated a particle converter composed of carbon and tantalum.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This yielded a total $1.5\times 10^{13}$ electron-positron pairs via a particle shower process.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The produced pair beams have a volume that fills multiple Debye spheres and are thus able to sustain collective plasma oscillations.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The existence of the antiproton was experimentally confirmed in 1955 by University of California, Berkeley physicists Emilio Segrè and Owen Chamberlain, for which they were awarded the 1959 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] An antiproton consists of two up antiquarks and one down antiquark (uud).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The properties of the antiproton that have been measured all match the corresponding properties of the proton, with the exception of the antiproton having opposite electric charge and magnetic moment from the proton.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Shortly afterwards, in 1956, the antineutron was discovered in proton–proton collisions at the Bevatron (Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory) by Bruce Cork and colleagues.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In addition to antibaryons, anti-nuclei consisting of multiple bound antiprotons and antineutrons have been created.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] These are typically produced at energies far too high to form antimatter atoms (with bound positrons in place of electrons).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In 1965, a group of researchers led by Antonino Zichichi reported production of nuclei of antideuterium at the Proton Synchrotron at CERN.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] At roughly the same time, observations of antideuterium nuclei were reported by a group of American physicists at the Alternating Gradient Synchrotron at Brookhaven National Laboratory.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In 1995, CERN announced that it had successfully brought into existence nine hot antihydrogen atoms by implementing the SLAC/Fermilab concept during the PS210 experiment.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The experiment was performed using the Low Energy Antiproton Ring (LEAR), and was led by Walter Oelert and Mario Macri.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Fermilab soon confirmed the CERN findings by producing approximately 100 antihydrogen atoms at their facilities.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The antihydrogen atoms created during PS210 and subsequent experiments (at both CERN and Fermilab) were extremely energetic and were not well suited to study.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] To resolve this hurdle, and to gain a better understanding of antihydrogen, two collaborations were formed in the late 1990s, namely, ATHENA and ATRAP.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In 1999, CERN activated the Antiproton Decelerator, a device capable of decelerating antiprotons from 3.5 GeV to 5.3 MeV – still too "hot" to produce study-effective antihydrogen, but a huge leap forward.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In late 2002 the ATHENA project announced that they had created the world's first "cold" antihydrogen.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The ATRAP project released similar results very shortly thereafter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The antiprotons used in these experiments were cooled by decelerating them with the Antiproton Decelerator, passing them through a thin sheet of foil, and finally capturing them in a Penning–Malmberg trap.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The overall cooling process is workable, but highly inefficient; approximately 25 million antiprotons leave the Antiproton Decelerator and roughly 25,000 make it to the Penning–Malmberg trap, which is about ⁠1/1000⁠ or 0.1% of the original amount.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The antiprotons are still hot when initially trapped.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] To cool them further, they are mixed into an electron plasma.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The electrons in this plasma cool via cyclotron radiation, and then sympathetically cool the antiprotons via Coulomb collisions.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Eventually, the electrons are removed by the application of short-duration electric fields, leaving the antiprotons with energies less than 100 meV.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] While the antiprotons are being cooled in the first trap, a small cloud of positrons is captured from radioactive sodium in a Surko-style positron accumulator.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This cloud is then recaptured in a second trap near the antiprotons.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Manipulations of the trap electrodes then tip the antiprotons into the positron plasma, where some combine with antiprotons to form antihydrogen.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This neutral antihydrogen is unaffected by the electric and magnetic fields used to trap the charged positrons and antiprotons, and within a few microseconds the antihydrogen hits the trap walls, where it annihilates.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Some hundreds of millions of antihydrogen atoms have been made in this fashion.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In 2005, ATHENA disbanded and some of the former members (along with others) formed the ALPHA Collaboration, which is also based at CERN.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The ultimate goal of this endeavour is to test CPT symmetry through comparison of the atomic spectra of hydrogen and antihydrogen (see hydrogen spectral series).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Most of the sought-after high-precision tests of the properties of antihydrogen could only be performed if the antihydrogen were trapped, that is, held in place for a relatively long time.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] While antihydrogen atoms are electrically neutral, the spins of their component particles produce a magnetic moment.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] These magnetic moments can interact with an inhomogeneous magnetic field; some of the antihydrogen atoms can be attracted to a magnetic minimum.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Such a minimum can be created by a combination of mirror and multipole fields.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antihydrogen can be trapped in such a magnetic minimum (minimum-B) trap; in November 2010, the ALPHA collaboration announced that they had so trapped 38 antihydrogen atoms for about a sixth of a second.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This was the first time that neutral antimatter had been trapped.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] On 26 April 2011, ALPHA announced that they had trapped 309 antihydrogen atoms, some for as long as 1,000 seconds (about 17 minutes).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This was longer than neutral antimatter had ever been trapped before.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] ALPHA has used these trapped atoms to initiate research into the spectral properties of antihydrogen.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In 2016, a new antiproton decelerator and cooler called ELENA (extra low energy antiproton decelerator) was built.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] It takes the antiprotons from the antiproton decelerator and cools them to 90 keV, which is "cold" enough to study.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This machine works by using high energy and accelerating the particles within the chamber.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] More than one hundred antiprotons can be captured per second, a huge improvement, but it would still take several thousand years to make a nanogram of antimatter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The biggest limiting factor in the large-scale production of antimatter is the availability of antiprotons.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Recent data released by CERN states that, when fully operational, their facilities are capable of producing ten million antiprotons per minute.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Assuming a 100% conversion of antiprotons to antihydrogen, it would take 100 billion years to produce 1 gram or 1 mole of antihydrogen (approximately 6.02×1023 atoms of antihydrogen).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] However, CERN only produces 1% of the antimatter Fermilab does, and neither are designed to produce antimatter.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] According to Gerald Jackson, using technology already in use today we are capable of producing and capturing 20 grams of antimatter particles per year at a yearly cost of 670 million dollars per facility.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antihelium-3 nuclei (3 He, i.e. two antiprotons and one antineutron) were first observed in the 1970s in proton–nucleus collision experiments at the Institute for High Energy Physics by Y.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Prockoshkin's group (Protvino near Moscow, USSR) and later created in nucleus–nucleus collision experiments.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Nucleus–nucleus collisions produce antinuclei through the coalescence of antiprotons and antineutrons created in these reactions.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In 2011, the STAR detector reported the observation of artificially created antihelium-4 nuclei (anti-alpha particles) (4 He) from such collisions.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer on the International Space Station has, as of 2021, recorded eight events that seem to indicate the detection of antihelium-3.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antimatter cannot be stored in a container made of ordinary matter because antimatter reacts with any matter it touches, annihilating itself and an equal amount of the container.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antimatter in the form of charged particles can be contained by a combination of electric and magnetic fields, in a device called a Penning trap.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This device cannot, however, contain antimatter that consists of uncharged particles, for which atomic traps are used.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In particular, such a trap may use the dipole moment (electric or magnetic) of the trapped particles.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] At high vacuum, the matter or antimatter particles can be trapped and cooled with slightly off-resonant laser radiation using a magneto-optical trap or magnetic trap.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Small particles can also be suspended with optical tweezers, using a highly focused laser beam.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The record for storing antiparticles is currently held by the TRAP experiment at CERN: antiprotons were kept in a Penning trap for 405 days.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] CERN scientists have demonstrated the transportation of 92 antiprotons for a distance of about five miles using BASE-STEP, a 1,000 kg (2,200 lb) truck-mounted cryogenic Penning trap apparatus, paving the way for practical shipments of antimatter to other institutions for study.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Scientists claim that antimatter is the costliest material to make.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In 2006, Gerald Smith estimated $250 million could produce 10 milligrams of positrons (equivalent to $25 billion per gram); in 1999, NASA gave a figure of $62.5 trillion per gram of antihydrogen.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] This is because production is difficult (only very few antiprotons are produced in reactions in particle accelerators) and because there is higher demand for other uses of particle accelerators.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] According to CERN, it has cost a few hundred million Swiss francs to produce about 1 billionth of a gram (the amount used so far for particle/antiparticle collisions).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In comparison, to produce the first atomic weapon, the cost of the Manhattan Project was estimated at $23 billion with inflation during 2007.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Several studies funded by NASA Innovative Advanced Concepts are exploring whether it might be possible to use magnetic scoops to collect the antimatter that occurs naturally in the Van Allen belt of the Earth, and ultimately the belts of gas giants like Jupiter, ideally at a lower cost per gram.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Matter–antimatter reactions have practical applications in medical imaging, such as positron emission tomography (PET).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In positive beta decay, a nuclide loses surplus positive charge by emitting a positron (in the same event, a proton becomes a neutron, and a neutrino is also emitted).
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Nuclides with surplus positive charge are easily made in a cyclotron and are widely generated for medical use.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antiprotons have also been shown within laboratory experiments to have the potential to treat certain cancers, in a similar method currently used for ion (proton) therapy.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Isolated and stored antimatter could be used as a fuel for interplanetary or interstellar travel as part of an antimatter-catalyzed nuclear pulse propulsion or another antimatter rocket.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Since the energy density of antimatter is higher than that of conventional fuels, an antimatter-fueled spacecraft would have a higher thrust-to-weight ratio than a conventional spacecraft.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] If matter–antimatter collisions resulted only in photon emission, the entire rest mass of the particles would be converted to kinetic energy.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Not all of that energy can be utilized by any realistic propulsion technology because of the nature of the annihilation products.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] While electron–positron reactions result in gamma ray photons, these are difficult to direct and use for thrust.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] In reactions between protons and antiprotons, their energy is converted largely into relativistic neutral and charged pions.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] The neutral pions decay almost immediately (with a lifetime of 85 attoseconds) into high-energy photons, but the charged pions decay more slowly (with a lifetime of 26 nanoseconds) and can be deflected magnetically to produce thrust.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Antimatter has been considered as a trigger mechanism for nuclear weapons.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] A major obstacle is the difficulty of producing antimatter in large enough quantities, and there is no evidence that it will ever be feasible.
[src:particle-physics/antimatter] Air Force funded studies of the physics of antimatter in the Cold War, and began considering its possible use in weapons, not just as a trigger, but as the explosive itself.
[src:particle-physics/boson] In particle physics, a **boson** (/ˈboʊzɒn/ /ˈboʊsɒn/) is a subatomic particle whose spin quantum number has an integer value (0, 1, 2, ...).
[src:particle-physics/boson] The class of bosons is one of the two fundamental classes of subatomic particle, the other being fermions, which have half odd-integer spin (1/2, 3/2, 5/2, ...).
[src:particle-physics/boson] Every observed subatomic particle is either a boson or a fermion.
[src:particle-physics/boson] Paul Dirac coined the term *boson* to classify the fundamental particles that obey Bose–Einstein statistics, the quantum framework pioneered by Satyendra Nath Bose.
[src:particle-physics/boson] Some bosons are elementary particles occupying a special role in particle physics, distinct from the role of fermions (which are sometimes described as the constituents of "ordinary matter").
[src:particle-physics/boson] Certain elementary bosons (e.g. gluons) act as force carriers, which give rise to forces between other particles, while one (the Higgs boson) contributes to the phenomenon of mass.
[src:particle-physics/boson] Other bosons, such as mesons, are composite particles made up of smaller constituents.
[src:particle-physics/boson] Outside the realm of particle physics, multiple identical composite bosons behave at high densities or low temperatures in a characteristic manner described by Bose–Einstein statistics: for example, a gas of helium-4 atoms becomes a superfluid at temperatures close to absolute zero.
[src:particle-physics/boson] Similarly, superconductivity arises because some quasiparticles, such as Cooper pairs, behave in this characteristic manner.
[src:particle-physics/boson] The term *boson* was coined by Paul Dirac to classify the fundamental particles that obey Bose–Einstein statistics, a quantum framework pioneered by the Indian physicist Satyendra Nath Bose.
[src:particle-physics/boson] While serving as a reader (later professor) at the University of Dhaka in Bengal (now in Bangladesh), Bose achieved a fundamental breakthrough: by treating photons as identical and indistinguishable particles, he independently derived Planck's law without relying on classical physics.
[src:particle-physics/boson] He sent this foundational manuscript to Albert Einstein, whose subsequent translation and endorsement of the work led to the formal development of the statistics and the theoretical prediction of the Bose–Einstein condensate.
[src:particle-physics/boson] All observed elementary particles are either bosons (with integer spin) or fermions (with odd half-integer spin).
[src:particle-physics/boson] Whereas the elementary particles that make up ordinary matter (leptons and quarks) are fermions, elementary bosons occupy a special role in particle physics.
[src:particle-physics/boson] They act either as force carriers which give rise to forces between other particles, or in one case give rise to the phenomenon of mass.
[src:particle-physics/boson] A *second-order tensor boson* (spin = 2) called the graviton (G) has been hypothesised as the force carrier for gravity, but so far all attempts to incorporate gravity into the Standard Model have failed.
[src:particle-physics/boson] Composite particles (such as hadrons, nuclei, and atoms) can be bosons or fermions depending on their constituents.
[src:particle-physics/boson] Since bosons have integer spin and fermions half odd-integer spin, any composite particle made up of an *even* number of fermions is a boson (e.g., 1/2 + 1/2 + 1/2 + 1/2 = 2 for the three quarks and an electron in a hydrogen atom).
[src:particle-physics/boson] As quantum particles, the behaviour of multiple indistinguishable bosons at high densities is described by Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:particle-physics/boson] One characteristic which becomes important in superfluidity and other applications of Bose–Einstein condensates is that there is no restriction on the number of bosons that may occupy the same quantum state.
[src:particle-physics/boson] As a consequence, when for example a gas of helium-4 atoms is cooled to temperatures very close to absolute zero and the kinetic energy of the particles becomes negligible, it condenses into a low-energy state and becomes a superfluid.
[src:particle-physics/boson] Other examples in condensed matter systems include Cooper pairs in superconductors and excitons in semiconductors.
[src:particle-physics/boson] Certain quasiparticles are observed to behave as bosons and to follow Bose–Einstein statistics, including Cooper pairs, plasmons and phonons.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] In the Standard Model of particle physics, an **elementary particle** or **fundamental particle** is a subatomic particle that is not composed of other particles.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The Standard Model recognizes seventeen distinct particles—twelve fermions and five bosons.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] As a consequence of flavor and color combinations and antimatter, the fermions and bosons are known to have 48 and 13 variations, respectively.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] These 61 elementary particles include electrons and other leptons, quarks, and the fundamental bosons.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Subatomic particles such as protons or neutrons, which contain two or more elementary particles, are known as composite particles.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The concept of an elementary particle is not based on measurements but instead depends on a theoretical framework.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Ordinary matter is composed of atoms, themselves once thought to be indivisible elementary particles.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The name *atom* comes from the Ancient Greek word *ἄτομος* (atomos) which means *indivisible* or *uncuttable*.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Despite the theories about atoms that had existed for thousands of years, their factual existence remained controversial until 1905.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] In that year, Albert Einstein published his paper on Brownian motion, putting to rest theories that had regarded molecules as mathematical illusions.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Einstein subsequently identified matter as ultimately composed of various concentrations of energy.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Subatomic constituents of the atom were first identified toward the end of the 19th century, beginning with the electron, followed by the proton in 1919, the photon in the 1920s, and the neutron in 1932.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] By that time, the advent of quantum mechanics had radically altered the definition of a "particle" by putting forward an understanding in which they carried out a simultaneous existence as matter waves.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Many theoretical elaborations upon, and beyond, the Standard Model have been made since its codification in the 1970s.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] These include notions of supersymmetry, which double the number of elementary particles by hypothesizing that each known particle associates with a "shadow" partner far more massive.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] However, like an additional elementary boson mediating gravitation, such superpartners remain undiscovered as of 2026.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] All elementary particles are either fermions or bosons.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] These classes are distinguished by their quantum statistics: fermions obey Fermi–Dirac statistics and bosons obey Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Their spin is differentiated via the spin–statistics theorem: it is half-integer for fermions, and integer for bosons.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] In the Standard Model, elementary particles are represented for predictive utility as point particles.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Though extremely successful, the Standard Model is limited by its omission of gravitation and has some parameters arbitrarily added but unexplained.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] According to the current models of Big Bang nucleosynthesis, the primordial composition of visible matter of the universe should be about 75% hydrogen and 25% helium-4 (in mass).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Neutrons are made of one up and two down quarks, while protons are made of two up and one down quark.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Since the other common elementary particles (such as electrons, neutrinos, or weak bosons) are so light or so rare when compared to atomic nuclei, we can neglect their mass contribution to the observable universe's total mass.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Therefore, one can conclude that most of the visible mass of the universe consists of protons and neutrons, which, like all baryons, in turn consist of up quarks and down quarks.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Some estimates imply that there are roughly 1080 baryons (almost entirely protons and neutrons) in the observable universe.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The number of protons in the observable universe is called the Eddington number.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] In terms of number of particles, some estimates imply that nearly all the matter, excluding dark matter, occurs in neutrinos, which constitute the majority of the roughly 1086 elementary particles of matter that exist in the visible universe.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Other estimates imply that roughly 1097 elementary particles exist in the visible universe (not including dark matter), mostly photons and other massless force carriers.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The Standard Model is widely considered to be a provisional theory rather than a truly fundamental one, however, since it is not known if it is compatible with Einstein's general relativity.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] There may be hypothetical elementary particles not described by the Standard Model, such as the graviton, the particle that would carry the gravitational force, and sparticles, supersymmetric partners of the ordinary particles.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The 12 fundamental fermions are divided into 3 generations of 4 particles each.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Half of the fermions are leptons, three of which have an electric charge of −1 *e*, called the electron (e− ), the muon (μ− ), and the tau (τ− ); the other three leptons are neutrinos (ν e, ν μ, ν τ), which are the only elementary fermions with neither electric nor color charge.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The remaining six particles are quarks (discussed below).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The following table lists current measured masses and mass estimates for all the fermions, using the same scale of measure: millions of electron-volts relative to square of light speed (MeV/*c*2).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] For example, the most accurately known quark mass is of the top quark (t) at 172.7 GeV/*c*2, estimated using the on-shell scheme.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Estimates of the values of quark masses depend on the version of quantum chromodynamics used to describe quark interactions.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Quarks are always confined in an envelope of gluons that confer vastly greater mass to the mesons and baryons where quarks occur, so values for quark masses cannot be measured directly.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Since their masses are so small compared to the effective mass of the surrounding gluons, slight differences in the calculation make large differences in the masses.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] There are also 12 fundamental fermionic antiparticles that correspond to these 12 particles.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] For example, the antielectron (positron) e+ is the electron's antiparticle and has an electric charge of +1 *e*.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Isolated quarks and antiquarks have never been detected, a fact explained by confinement.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Every quark carries one of three color charges of the strong interaction; antiquarks similarly carry anticolor.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Color-charged particles interact via gluon exchange in the same way that charged particles interact via photon exchange.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Gluons are themselves color-charged, however, resulting in an amplification of the strong force as color-charged particles are separated.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Unlike the electromagnetic force, which diminishes as charged particles separate, color-charged particles feel increasing force.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Nonetheless, color-charged particles may combine to form color neutral composite particles called hadrons.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] A quark may pair up with an antiquark: the quark has a color and the antiquark has the corresponding anticolor.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The color and anticolor cancel out, forming a color neutral meson.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Alternatively, three quarks can exist together, one quark being "red", another "blue", another "green".
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] These three colored quarks together form a color-neutral baryon.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Symmetrically, three antiquarks with the colors "antired", "antiblue" and "antigreen" can form a color-neutral antibaryon.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Quarks also carry fractional electric charges, but, since they are confined within hadrons whose charges are all integral, fractional charges have never been isolated.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Note that quarks have electric charges of either ⁠++2/3⁠ *e* or ⁠−+1/3⁠ *e*, whereas antiquarks have corresponding electric charges of either ⁠−+2/3⁠ *e* or ⁠++1/3⁠ *e*.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Evidence for the existence of quarks comes from deep inelastic scattering: firing electrons at nuclei to determine the distribution of charge within nucleons (which are baryons).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] If the charge is uniform, the electric field around the proton should be uniform and the electron should scatter elastically.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Low-energy electrons do scatter in this way, but, above a particular energy, the protons deflect some electrons through large angles.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The recoiling electron has much less energy and a jet of particles is emitted.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] This inelastic scattering suggests that the charge in the proton is not uniform but split among smaller charged particles: quarks.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] In the Standard Model, vector (spin-1) bosons (gluons, photons, and the W and Z bosons) mediate forces, whereas the Higgs boson (spin-0) is responsible for the intrinsic mass of particles.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Bosons differ from fermions in the fact that multiple bosons can occupy the same quantum state (Pauli exclusion principle).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Also, bosons can be either elementary, like photons, or a combination, like mesons.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The spin of bosons are integers instead of half integers.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Gluons mediate the strong interaction, which join quarks and thereby form hadrons, which are either baryons (three quarks) or mesons (one quark and one antiquark).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Protons and neutrons are baryons, joined by gluons to form the atomic nucleus.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Like quarks, gluons exhibit color and anticolor – unrelated to the concept of visual color and rather the particles' strong interactions – sometimes in combinations, altogether eight variations of gluons.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] There are three weak gauge bosons: W+, W−, and Z0; these mediate the weak interaction.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The W bosons are known for their mediation in nuclear decay: The W− converts a neutron into a proton then decays into an electron and electron-antineutrino pair.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The Z0 does not convert particle flavor or charges, but rather changes momentum; it is the only mechanism for elastically scattering neutrinos.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The weak gauge bosons were discovered due to momentum change in electrons from neutrino-Z exchange.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The massless photon mediates the electromagnetic interaction.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] These four gauge bosons form the electroweak interaction among elementary particles.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Although the weak and electromagnetic forces appear quite different to us at everyday energies, the two forces are theorized to unify as a single electroweak force at high energies.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] This prediction was clearly confirmed by measurements of cross-sections for high-energy electron-proton scattering at the HERA collider at DESY.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The differences at low energies is a consequence of the high masses of the W and Z bosons, which in turn are a consequence of the Higgs mechanism.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Through the process of spontaneous symmetry breaking, the Higgs selects a special direction in electroweak space that causes three electroweak particles to become very heavy (the weak bosons) and one to remain with an undefined rest mass as it is always in motion (the photon).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] On 4 July 2012, after many years of experimentally searching for evidence of its existence, the Higgs boson was announced to have been observed at CERN's Large Hadron Collider.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Peter Higgs who first posited the existence of the Higgs boson was present at the announcement.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The Higgs boson is believed to have a mass of approximately 125 GeV/*c*2.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The statistical significance of this discovery was reported as 5 sigma, which implies a certainty of roughly 99.99994%.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] In particle physics, this is the level of significance required to officially label experimental observations as a discovery.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Research into the properties of the newly discovered particle continues.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Although experimental evidence overwhelmingly confirms the Standard Model’s predictions, some aspects of the theory remain poorly understood, such as the reason for the extremely large discrepancy between the weak force and gravity (an aspect of the hierarchy problem).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] A further issue is the fact that several of the parameters of the theory were introduced *ad hoc* rather than emerging naturally from an underlying physical explanation.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Theories beyond the Standard Model attempt to resolve these perceived shortcomings.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The graviton is a hypothetical elementary spin-2 particle proposed to mediate gravitation.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] While it remains undiscovered due to the difficulty inherent in its detection, it is sometimes included in tables of elementary particles.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The conventional graviton is massless, although some models containing massive Kaluza–Klein gravitons exist.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] One extension of the Standard Model attempts to combine the electroweak interaction with the strong interaction into a single 'grand unified theory' (GUT).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Such a force would be spontaneously broken into the three forces by a Higgs-like mechanism.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] This breakdown is theorized to occur at high energies, making it difficult to observe unification in a laboratory.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The most dramatic prediction of grand unification is the existence of X and Y bosons, which cause proton decay.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The non-observation of proton decay at the Super-Kamiokande neutrino observatory rules out the simplest GUTs, however, including SU(5) and SO(10).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Supersymmetry extends the Standard Model by adding another class of symmetries to the Lagrangian.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] These symmetries exchange fermionic particles with bosonic ones.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Such a symmetry predicts the existence of supersymmetric particles, abbreviated as *sparticles*, which include the sleptons, squarks, neutralinos, and charginos.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Each particle in the Standard Model would have a superpartner whose spin differs by 1⁄2 from the ordinary particle.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Due to the breaking of supersymmetry, the sparticles are much heavier than their ordinary counterparts; they are so heavy that existing particle colliders would not be powerful enough to produce them.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Some physicists believe that sparticles will be detected by the Large Hadron Collider at CERN.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] String theory is a model of physics whereby all "particles" that make up matter are composed of strings (measuring at the Planck length) that exist in an 11-dimensional (according to M-theory, the leading version) or 12-dimensional (according to F-theory) universe.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] These strings vibrate at different frequencies that determine mass, electric charge, color charge, and spin.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] A "string" can be open (a line) or closed in a loop (a one-dimensional sphere, that is, a circle).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] As a string moves through space it sweeps out something called a *world sheet*.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] String theory proposes that our universe is merely a 4-brane, inside which exist the three space dimensions and the one time dimension that we observe.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The remaining 7 theoretical dimensions either are very tiny and curled up (and too small to be macroscopically accessible) or simply do not/cannot exist in our universe (because they exist in a grander scheme called the "multiverse" outside our known universe).
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Some predictions of the string theory include existence of extremely massive counterparts of ordinary particles due to vibrational excitations of the fundamental string and existence of a massless spin-2 particle behaving like the graviton.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Technicolor theories try to modify the Standard Model in a minimal way by introducing a new QCD-like interaction.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] This means one adds a new theory of so-called Techniquarks, interacting via so called Technigluons.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The main idea is that the Higgs boson is not an elementary particle but a bound state of these objects.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] According to preon theory there are one or more orders of particles more fundamental than those (or most of those) found in the Standard Model.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] The most fundamental of these are normally called preons, which is derived from "pre-quarks".
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] In essence, preon theory tries to do for the Standard Model what the Standard Model did for the particle zoo that came before it.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Most models assume that almost everything in the Standard Model can be explained in terms of three to six more fundamental particles and the rules that govern their interactions.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Interest in preons has waned since the simplest models were experimentally ruled out in the 1980s.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Accelerons are the hypothetical subatomic particles that integrally link the newfound mass of the neutrino to the dark energy conjectured to be accelerating the expansion of the universe.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] In this theory, neutrinos are influenced by a new force resulting from their interactions with accelerons, leading to dark energy.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Dark energy results as the universe tries to pull neutrinos apart.
[src:particle-physics/elementary-particle] Accelerons are thought to interact with matter more infrequently than they do with neutrinos.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] In particle physics, a **fermion** is a subatomic particle that follows Fermi–Dirac statistics.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] Fermions have a half-integer spin (spin ⁠1/2⁠, spin ⁠3/2⁠, etc.) and obey the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] These particles include all quarks and leptons and all composite particles made of an odd number of these, such as all baryons and many atoms and nuclei.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] Fermions differ from bosons, which obey Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] Some fermions are elementary particles (such as electrons), and some are composite particles (such as protons).
[src:particle-physics/fermion] For example, according to the spin-statistics theorem in relativistic quantum field theory, particles with integer spin are bosons.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] In contrast, particles with half-integer spin are fermions.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] In addition to the spin characteristic, fermions have another specific property: they possess conserved baryon or lepton quantum numbers.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] Therefore, what is usually referred to as the spin-statistics relation is, in fact, a spin statistics-quantum number relation.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] As a consequence of the Pauli exclusion principle, only one fermion can occupy a particular quantum state at a given time.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] Suppose multiple fermions have the same spatial probability distribution, then, at least one property of each fermion, such as its spin, must be different.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] Fermions are usually associated with matter, whereas bosons are generally force carrier particles.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] However, in the current state of particle physics, the distinction between the two concepts is unclear.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] Weakly interacting fermions can also display bosonic behavior under extreme conditions.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] For example, at low temperatures, fermions show superfluidity for uncharged particles and superconductivity for charged particles.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] Composite fermions, such as protons and neutrons, are the key building blocks of everyday matter.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] English theoretical physicist Paul Dirac coined the name fermion from the surname of Italian physicist Enrico Fermi.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] The Standard Model recognizes two types of elementary fermions: quarks and leptons.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] In all, the model distinguishes 24 different fermions.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] There are six quarks (up, down, strange, charm, bottom and top), and six leptons (electron, electron neutrino, muon, muon neutrino, tau and tau neutrino), along with the corresponding antiparticle of each of these.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] Most Standard Model fermions are believed to be Dirac fermions, although it is unknown at this time whether the neutrinos are Dirac or Majorana fermions (or both).
[src:particle-physics/fermion] Dirac fermions can be treated as a combination of two Weyl fermions.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] In July 2015, Weyl fermions were experimentally realized in Weyl semimetals.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] More precisely, because of the relation between spin and statistics, a particle containing an odd number of fermions is itself a fermion.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] The number of bosons within a composite particle made up of simple particles bound with a potential has no effect on whether it is a boson or a fermion.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] The fermionic or bosonic behaviour of a composite particle is only observed when the constituent particles remain far apart.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] When they are close together, the spatial structure becomes important and the composite particles behave according to their constituent makeup.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] Fermions can exhibit bosonic behavior when they become bound in pairs.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] This is the origin of superconductivity and the superfluidity of helium-3.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] In superconducting materials, electrons interact through the exchange of phonons, forming Cooper pairs, while in helium-3, the atoms interact and pair via spin fluctuations.
[src:particle-physics/fermion] The quasiparticles of the fractional quantum Hall effect are also known as composite fermions; they consist of electrons with an even number of quantized vortices attached to them.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] In particle physics, a **lepton** is an elementary particle of half-integer spin (spin ⁠1/2⁠) that does not undergo strong interactions.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Two main classes of leptons exist: charged leptons (also known as the electron-like leptons or muons), including the electron, muon, and tauon, and neutral leptons, better known as neutrinos.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Charged leptons can combine with other particles to form various composite particles such as atoms and positronium, while neutrinos rarely interact with anything, and are consequently rarely observed.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The best known of all leptons is the electron.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] There are six types of leptons, known as *flavours*, grouped in three *generations*.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Electrons have the least mass of all the charged leptons.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The heavier muons and taus will rapidly change into electrons and neutrinos through a process of particle decay: the transformation from a higher mass state to a lower mass state.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Thus electrons are stable and the most common charged lepton in the universe, whereas muons and taus can only be produced in high-energy collisions (such as those involving cosmic rays and those carried out in particle accelerators).
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Leptons have various intrinsic properties, including electric charge, spin, and mass.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] For every lepton flavor, there is a corresponding type of antiparticle, known as an antilepton, that differs from the lepton only in that some of its properties have equal magnitude but opposite sign.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] According to certain theories, neutrinos may be their own antiparticle.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] It is not currently known whether this is the case.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The first charged lepton, the electron, was theorized in the mid-19th century by several scientists and was discovered in 1897 by J.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The next lepton to be observed was the muon, discovered by Carl D.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Anderson in 1936, which was classified as a meson at the time.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] After investigation, it was realized that the muon did not have the expected properties of a meson, but rather behaved like an electron, only with higher mass.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] It took until 1947 for the concept of "leptons" as a family of particles to be proposed.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The first neutrino, the electron neutrino, was proposed by Wolfgang Pauli in 1930 to explain certain characteristics of beta decay.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] It was first observed in the Cowan–Reines neutrino experiment conducted by Clyde Cowan and Frederick Reines in 1956.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The muon neutrino was discovered in 1962 by Leon M.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Lederman, Melvin Schwartz, and Jack Steinberger, and the tau discovered between 1974 and 1977 by Martin Lewis Perl and his colleagues from the Stanford Linear Accelerator Center and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The tau neutrino remained elusive until July 2000, when the DONUT collaboration from Fermilab announced its discovery.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Leptons are an important part of the Standard Model.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Electrons are one of the components of atoms, alongside protons and neutrons.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Exotic atoms with muons and taus instead of electrons can also be synthesized, as well as lepton–antilepton particles such as positronium.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The name *lepton* comes from the Greek λεπτός *leptós*, "fine, small, thin" (neuter nominative/accusative singular form: λεπτόν *leptón*); the earliest attested form of the word is the Mycenaean Greek 𐀩𐀡𐀵, *re-po-to*, written in Linear B syllabic script.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Rosenfeld chose the name as the common name for electrons and (then hypothesized) neutrinos.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Additionally, the muon, initially classified as a meson, was reclassified as a lepton in the 1950s.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The masses of those particles are small compared to nucleons—the mass of an electron (0.511 MeV/*c*2) and the mass of a muon (with a value of 105.7 MeV/*c*2) are fractions of the mass of the "heavy" proton (938.3 MeV/*c*2), and the mass of a neutrino is nearly zero.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] However, the mass of the tau (discovered in the mid-1970s) (1777 MeV/*c*2) is nearly twice that of the proton and 3477‍ times that of the electron.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The first lepton identified was the electron, discovered by J.J.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Thomson and his team of British physicists in 1897.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Then in 1930, Wolfgang Pauli postulated the electron neutrino to preserve conservation of energy, conservation of momentum, and conservation of angular momentum in beta decay.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Pauli theorized that an undetected particle was carrying away the difference between the energy, momentum, and angular momentum of the initial and observed final particles.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The electron neutrino was simply called the neutrino, as it was not yet known that neutrinos came in different flavours (or different "generations").
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Nearly 40 years after the discovery of the electron, the muon was discovered by Carl D.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Due to its mass, it was initially categorized as a meson rather than a lepton.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] It later became clear that the muon was much more similar to the electron than to mesons, as muons do not undergo the strong interaction, and thus the muon was reclassified: electrons, muons, and the (electron) neutrino were grouped into a new group of particles—the leptons.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Lederman, Melvin Schwartz, and Jack Steinberger showed that more than one type of neutrino exists by first detecting interactions of the muon neutrino, which earned them the 1988 Nobel Prize, although by then the different flavours of neutrino had already been theorized.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The tau was first detected in a series of experiments between 1974 and 1977 by Martin Lewis Perl with his colleagues at the SLAC LBL group.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Like the electron and the muon, it too was expected to have an associated neutrino.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The first evidence for tau neutrinos came from the observation of "missing" energy and momentum in tau decay, analogous to the "missing" energy and momentum in beta decay leading to the discovery of the electron neutrino.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The first detection of tau neutrino interactions was announced in 2000 by the DONUT collaboration at Fermilab, making it the second-to-latest particle of the Standard Model to have been directly observed, with Higgs boson being discovered in 2012.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Although all present data is consistent with three generations of leptons, some particle physicists are searching for a fourth generation.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The current lower limit on the mass of such a fourth charged lepton is 100.8 GeV/*c*2, while its associated neutrino would have a mass of at least 45.0 GeV/*c*2.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The spin-statistics theorem thus implies that they are fermions and thus that they are subject to the Pauli exclusion principle: no two leptons of the same species can be in the same state at the same time.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Furthermore, it means that a lepton can have only two possible spin states, namely up or down.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] A closely related property is chirality, which in turn is closely related to a more easily visualized property called helicity.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The helicity of a particle is the direction of its spin relative to its momentum; particles with spin in the same direction as their momentum are called *right-handed* and they are otherwise called *left-handed*.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] When a particle is massless, the direction of its momentum relative to its spin is the same in every reference frame, whereas for massive particles it is possible to 'overtake' the particle by choosing a faster-moving reference frame; in the faster frame, the helicity is reversed.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Chirality is a technical property, defined through transformation behaviour under the Poincaré group, that does not change with reference frame.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] It is contrived to agree with helicity for massless particles, and is still well defined for particles with mass.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] In many quantum field theories, such as quantum electrodynamics and quantum chromodynamics, left- and right-handed fermions are identical.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] However, the Standard Model's weak interaction treats left-handed and right-handed fermions differently: only left-handed fermions (and right-handed anti-fermions) participate in the weak interaction.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] This is an example of parity violation explicitly written into the model.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] In the literature, left-handed fields are often denoted by a capital L subscript (e.g. the normal electron e− L) and right-handed fields are denoted by a capital R subscript (e.g. a positron e+ R).
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Even though electrically charged right-handed particles (electron, muon, or tau) do not engage in the weak interaction specifically, they can still interact electrically, and hence still participate in the combined electroweak force, although with different strengths (*Y*W).
[src:particle-physics/lepton] One of the most prominent properties of leptons is their electric charge, Q.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The electric charge determines the strength of their electromagnetic interactions.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] It determines the strength of the electric field generated by the particle (see Coulomb's law) and how strongly the particle reacts to an external electric or magnetic field (see Lorentz force).
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Each generation contains one lepton with *Q* = −1 *e* and one lepton with zero electric charge.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The lepton with electric charge is commonly simply referred to as a *charged lepton* while a neutral lepton is called a *neutrino*.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] For example, the first generation consists of the electron e− with a negative electric charge and the electrically neutral electron neutrino ν e.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] In the language of quantum field theory, the electromagnetic interaction of the charged leptons is expressed by the fact that the particles interact with the quantum of the electromagnetic field, the photon.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The Feynman diagram of the electron–photon interaction is shown on the right.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Because leptons possess an intrinsic rotation in the form of their spin, charged leptons generate a magnetic field.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] where m is the mass of the lepton and g is the so-called "g factor" for the lepton.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] First-order quantum mechanical approximation predicts that the magnitude of the g factor is 2 for all leptons.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] However, higher-order quantum effects caused by loops in Feynman diagrams introduce corrections to this value.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] These corrections, referred to as the *anomalous magnetic dipole moment*, are very sensitive to the details of a quantum field theory model, and thus provide the opportunity for precision tests of the Standard Model.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The theoretical and measured values for the *electron* anomalous magnetic dipole moment are within agreement within eight significant figures.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The results for the *muon*, however, are problematic, hinting at a small, persistent discrepancy between the Standard Model and experiment.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] In the Standard Model, the left-handed charged lepton and the left-handed neutrino are arranged in doublet that transforms in the spinor representation (*T* = ⁠ 1 /2⁠) of the weak isospin SU(2) gauge symmetry.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] This means that these particles are eigenstates of the isospin projection *T*3 with eigenvalues ⁠++ 1 /2⁠ and ⁠−+ 1 /2⁠ respectively.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] In the meantime, the right-handed charged lepton transforms as a weak isospin scalar (*T* = 0) and thus does not participate in the weak interaction, while there is no evidence that a right-handed neutrino exists at all.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The Higgs mechanism recombines the gauge fields of the weak isospin SU(2) and the weak hypercharge U(1) symmetries to three massive vector bosons (W+ , W− , Z0 ) mediating the weak interaction, and one massless vector boson, the photon (γ), responsible for the electromagnetic interaction.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] To recover the observed electric charges for all particles, the left-handed weak isospin doublet (νeL, e− L) must thus have *Y*W = −1, while the right-handed isospin scalar e− R must have *Y*W = −2.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The interaction of the leptons with the massive weak interaction vector bosons is shown in the figure on the right.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] In the Standard Model, each lepton starts out with no intrinsic mass.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The charged leptons (i.e. the electron, muon, and tau) obtain an effective mass through interaction with the Higgs field, but the neutrinos remain massless.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] For technical reasons, the masslessness of the neutrinos implies that there is no mixing of the different generations of charged leptons as there is for quarks.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The zero mass of neutrino is in close agreement with current direct experimental observations of the mass.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] However, it is known from indirect experiments—most prominently from observed neutrino oscillations—that neutrinos have to have a nonzero mass, probably less than 2 eV/*c*2.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] This implies the existence of physics beyond the Standard Model.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The currently most favoured extension is the so-called seesaw mechanism, which would explain both why the left-handed neutrinos are so light compared to the corresponding charged leptons, and why we have not yet seen any right-handed neutrinos.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The members of each generation's weak isospin doublet are assigned leptonic numbers that are conserved under the Standard Model.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Electrons and electron neutrinos have an *electronic number* of *L*e = 1, while muons and muon neutrinos have a *muonic number* of *L*μ = 1, while tau particles and tau neutrinos have a *tauonic number* of *L*τ = 1.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The antileptons have their respective generation's leptonic numbers of −1.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Conservation of the leptonic numbers means that the number of leptons of the same type remains the same, when particles interact.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] This implies that leptons and antileptons must be created in pairs of a single generation.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] However, neutrino oscillations are known to violate the conservation of the individual leptonic numbers.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Such a violation is considered to be smoking gun evidence for physics beyond the Standard Model.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] A much stronger conservation law is the conservation of the total number of leptons (L with *no* subscript), conserved even in the case of neutrino oscillations, but even it is still violated by a tiny amount by the chiral anomaly.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The coupling of leptons to all types of gauge boson are flavour-independent: The interaction between leptons and a gauge boson measures the same for each lepton.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] This property is called **lepton universality** and has been tested in measurements of the muon and tau lifetimes and of Z boson partial decay widths, particularly at the Stanford Linear Collider (SLC) and Large Electron–Positron Collider (LEP) experiments.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] where K2 is some constant, and GF is the Fermi coupling constant.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Muon–tauon universality implies that K2 ≈ K3.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The branching ratios for the electronic mode (17.82%) and muonic (17.39%) mode of tau decay are not equal due to the mass difference of the final state leptons.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Universality also accounts for the ratio of muon and tau lifetimes.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] where $\;{\mathcal {B}}(x\rightarrow y)\;$ denotes the branching ratios and $\;\Gamma (x\rightarrow y)\;$ denotes the resonance width of the process $\;x\rightarrow y~,$ with x and y replaced by two different particles from "e" or "μ" or "τ".
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Using values from the 2008 *Review of Particle Physics* for the branching ratios of the muon and tau yields a lifetime ratio of ~ 1.29×10−7, comparable to the measured lifetime ratio of ~ 1.32×10−7.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] The difference is due to K2 and K3 not *actually* being constants: They depend slightly on the mass of leptons involved.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] Recent tests of lepton universality in B meson decays, performed by the LHCb, BaBar, and Belle experiments, have shown consistent deviations from the Standard Model predictions.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] However the combined statistical and systematic significance is not yet high enough to claim an observation of new physics.
[src:particle-physics/lepton] In 2024 a preprint by the ATLAS collaboration has published a new value of $R_{W}^{\mu /e}={\mathcal {B}}(W\rightarrow \mu \nu _{\mu })/{\mathcal {B}}(W\rightarrow e\nu _{e})=0.9995\pm 0.0045$ the most precise ratio so far testing the lepton flavour universality.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The fundamental particles in the universe are classified in the Standard Model as fermions (matter particles) and bosons (force-carrying particles).
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] There are three generations of fermions, although ordinary matter is made only from the first fermion generation.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The first generation consists of up and down quarks which form protons and neutrons, and electrons and electron neutrinos.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The three fundamental interactions known to be mediated by bosons are electromagnetism, the weak interaction, and the strong interaction.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Quarks form hadrons, but cannot exist on their own.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Hadrons that contain an odd number of quarks are called baryons and those that contain an even number are called mesons.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Two baryons, the proton and the neutron, make up most of the mass of ordinary matter.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Mesons are unstable and the longest-lived last for only a few hundredths of a microsecond.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] They occur after collisions between particles made of quarks, such as fast-moving protons and neutrons in cosmic rays.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Mesons are also produced in cyclotrons or other particle accelerators.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Particles have corresponding antiparticles with the same mass but with opposite electric charges.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] For example, the antiparticle of the electron is the positron.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The electron has a negative electric charge, the positron has a positive charge.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] These antiparticles can theoretically form a corresponding form of matter called antimatter.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Some particles, such as the photon, are their own antiparticle.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] These elementary particles are excitations of the quantum fields that also govern their interactions.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The dominant theory explaining these fundamental particles and fields, along with their dynamics, is called the Standard Model.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The reconciliation of gravity to the current particle physics theory is not solved; many theories have addressed this problem, such as loop quantum gravity, string theory and supersymmetry theory.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Experimental particle physics is the study of these particles in radioactive processes and in particle accelerators such as the Large Hadron Collider.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Theoretical particle physics is the study of these particles in the context of cosmology and quantum theory.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The two are closely interrelated: the Higgs boson was postulated theoretically before being confirmed by experiments.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The idea that all matter is fundamentally composed of elementary particles dates from at least the 6th century BC.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] In the 19th century, John Dalton, through his work on stoichiometry, concluded that each element of nature was composed of a single, unique type of particle.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The early 20th century explorations of nuclear physics and quantum physics led to proofs of nuclear fission in 1939 by Lise Meitner (based on experiments by Otto Hahn), and nuclear fusion by Hans Bethe in that same year; both discoveries also led to the development of nuclear weapons.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Bethe's 1947 calculation of the Lamb shift is credited with having "opened the way to the modern era of particle physics".
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Throughout the 1950s and 1960s, a bewildering variety of particles was found in collisions of particles from beams of increasingly high energy.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] It was referred to informally as the *particle zoo*.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Important discoveries such as the CP violation by James Cronin and Val Fitch brought new questions to matter-antimatter imbalance.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] After the formulation of the Standard Model during the 1970s, physicists clarified the origin of the particle zoo.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The large number of particles was explained as combinations of a (relatively) small number of more fundamental particles and framed in the context of quantum field theories.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] This reclassification marked the beginning of modern particle physics.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The current state of the classification of all elementary particles is explained by the Standard Model, which gained widespread acceptance in the mid-1970s after experimental confirmation of the existence of quarks.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] It describes the strong, weak, and electromagnetic fundamental interactions, using mediating gauge bosons.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The species of gauge bosons are eight gluons, W− , W+ and Z bosons, and the photon.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The Standard Model also contains 24 fundamental fermions (12 particles and their associated anti-particles), which are the constituents of all matter.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Finally, the Standard Model also predicted the existence of a type of boson known as the Higgs boson.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] On 4 July 2012, physicists with the Large Hadron Collider at CERN announced they had found a new particle that behaves similarly to what is expected from the Higgs boson.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The Standard Model, as currently formulated, has 61 elementary particles.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Those elementary particles can combine to form composite particles, accounting for the hundreds of other species of particles that have been discovered since the 1960s.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The Standard Model has been found to agree with almost all the experimental tests conducted to date.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] However, most particle physicists believe that it is an incomplete description of nature and that a more fundamental theory awaits discovery (See Theory of Everything).
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] In recent years, measurements of neutrino mass have provided the first experimental deviations from the Standard Model, since neutrinos do not have mass in the Standard Model.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] All particles and their interactions observed to date can be described almost entirely by the Standard Model.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Dynamics of particles are also governed by quantum mechanics; they exhibit wave–particle duality, displaying particle-like behaviour under certain experimental conditions and wave-like behaviour in others.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] In more technical terms, they are described by quantum state vectors in a Hilbert space, which is also treated in quantum field theory.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Following the convention of particle physicists, the term *elementary particles* is applied to those particles that are, according to current understanding, presumed to be indivisible and not composed of other particles.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Ordinary matter is made from first-generation quarks (up, down) and leptons (electron, electron neutrino).
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Collectively, quarks and leptons are called fermions.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] They have a quantum spin of half-integers (−1/2, 1/2, 3/2, etc.) and obey the Pauli exclusion principle, where no two particles may occupy the same quantum state.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Quarks have fractional elementary electric charge (−1/3 or 2/3) and leptons have whole-numbered electric charge (0 or -1).
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Quarks also have color charge, which is labeled arbitrarily with no correlation to actual light color as red, green and blue.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Because the interactions between the quarks store energy which can convert to other particles when the quarks are far apart enough, quarks cannot be observed independently.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] There are three known generations of quarks (up and down, strange and charm, top and bottom) and leptons (electron and its neutrino, muon and its neutrino, tau and its neutrino), with strong indirect evidence that a fourth generation of fermions does not exist.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Bosons are the mediators or carriers of fundamental interactions, such as electromagnetism, the weak interaction, and the strong interaction.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Electromagnetism is mediated by the photon, the quanta of light.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The weak interaction is mediated by the W and Z bosons.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The strong interaction is mediated by the gluon, which can link quarks together to form composite particles.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Due to the aforementioned color confinement, gluons are never observed independently.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The Higgs boson gives mass to the W and Z bosons via the Higgs mechanism – the gluon and photon are expected to be massless.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] All bosons have an integer quantum spin (0 and 1) and can have the same quantum state.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Most aforementioned particles have corresponding antiparticles, which compose antimatter.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Normal particles have positive lepton or baryon number, and antiparticles have these numbers negative.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Most properties of corresponding antiparticles and particles are the same, with a few gets reversed; the electron's antiparticle, positron, has an opposite charge.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] To differentiate between antiparticles and particles, a plus or negative sign is added in superscript.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] For example, the electron and the positron are denoted e− and e+ , respectively.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] However, in the case that the particle has a charge of 0 (equal to that of the antiparticle), the antiparticle is denoted with a line above the symbol.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] As such, an electron neutrino is ν e, whereas its antineutrino is ν e.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] When a particle and an antiparticle interact with each other, they are annihilated and convert to other particles.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Some particles, such as the photon or gluon, have no antiparticles.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Quarks and gluons additionally have color charges, which influences the strong interaction.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Quark's color charges are called red, green and blue (though the particle itself have no physical color), and in antiquarks are called antired, antigreen and antiblue.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The gluon can have eight color charges, which are the result of quarks' interactions to form composite particles (gauge symmetry SU(3)).
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The neutrons and protons in the atomic nuclei are baryons – the neutron is composed of two down quarks and one up quark, and the proton is composed of two up quarks and one down quark.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] A baryon is composed of three quarks, and a meson is composed of two quarks (one normal, one anti).
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Baryons and mesons are collectively called hadrons.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Quarks inside hadrons are governed by the strong interaction, thus are subjected to quantum chromodynamics (color charges).
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The bounded quarks must have their color charge to be neutral, or "white" for analogy with mixing the primary colors.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] More exotic hadrons can have other types, arrangement or number of quarks (tetraquark, pentaquark).
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] An atom is made from protons, neutrons and electrons.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] By modifying the particles inside a normal atom, exotic atoms can be formed.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] A simple example would be the hydrogen-4.1, which has one of its electrons replaced with a muon.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The graviton is a hypothetical particle that can mediate the gravitational interaction, but it has not been detected or completely reconciled with current theories.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Many other hypothetical particles have been proposed to address the limitations of the Standard Model.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Notably, supersymmetric particles aim to solve the hierarchy problem, axions address the strong CP problem, and various other particles are proposed to explain the origins of dark matter and dark energy.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] As with theoretical physics, theoretical particle physics attempts to develop the models, theoretical framework, and mathematical tools to understand current experiments and make predictions for future experiments.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] There are several major interrelated efforts being made in theoretical particle physics today.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] One important branch attempts to better understand the Standard Model and its tests.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Theorists make quantitative predictions of observables at collider and astronomical experiments, which along with experimental measurements is used to extract the parameters of the Standard Model with less uncertainty.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] This work probes the limits of the Standard Model and therefore expands scientific understanding of nature's building blocks.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Those efforts are made challenging by the difficulty of calculating high precision quantities in quantum chromodynamics.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Some theorists working in this area use the tools of perturbative quantum field theory and effective field theory, referring to themselves as phenomenologists.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Others make use of lattice field theory and call themselves *lattice theorists*.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Another major effort is in model building where model builders develop ideas for what physics may lie beyond the Standard Model (at higher energies or smaller distances).
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] This work is often motivated by the hierarchy problem and is constrained by existing experimental data.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] It may involve work on supersymmetry, alternatives to the Higgs mechanism, extra spatial dimensions (such as the Randall–Sundrum models), Preon theory, combinations of these, or other ideas.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Vanishing-dimensions theory is a particle physics theory suggesting that systems with higher energy have a smaller number of dimensions.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] A third major effort in theoretical particle physics is string theory.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] *String theorists* attempt to construct a unified description of quantum mechanics and general relativity by building a theory based on small strings, and branes rather than particles.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] If the theory is successful, it may be considered a "Theory of Everything", or "TOE".
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] There are other areas of work in theoretical particle physics ranging from particle cosmology to loop quantum gravity.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] In principle, all physics (and practical applications developed therefrom) can be derived from the study of fundamental particles.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] In practice, even if "particle physics" is taken to mean only "high-energy atom smashers", many technologies have been developed during these pioneering investigations that later find wide uses in society.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Particle accelerators are used to produce medical isotopes for research and treatment (for example, isotopes used in PET imaging), or used directly in external beam radiotherapy.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The development of superconductors has been pushed forward by their use in particle physics.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] The World Wide Web and touchscreen technology were initially developed at CERN.
[src:particle-physics/particle-physics] Additional applications are found in medicine, national security, industry, computing, science, and workforce development, illustrating a long and growing list of beneficial practical applications with contributions from particle physics.
[src:particle-physics/quark] A **quark** (/ˈkwɔːrk, ˈkwɑːrk/ ⓘ) is a type of elementary particle and a fundamental constituent of matter.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Quarks combine to form composite particles called hadrons, the most stable of which are protons and neutrons, the components of atomic nuclei.
[src:particle-physics/quark] All commonly observable matter is composed of up quarks, down quarks, and electrons.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Owing to a phenomenon known as *color confinement*, quarks are never found in isolation; they can be found only within hadrons, which include baryons (such as protons and neutrons) and mesons, or in quark–gluon plasmas.
[src:particle-physics/quark] For this reason, much of what is known about quarks has been drawn from observations of hadrons.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Quarks have various intrinsic properties, including electric charge, mass, color charge, and spin.
[src:particle-physics/quark] There are six types, known as *flavors*, of quarks: up, down, charm, strange, top, and bottom.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Up and down quarks have the lowest masses of all quarks.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The heavier quarks rapidly change into up and down quarks through a process of particle decay: the transformation from a higher mass state to a lower mass state.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Because of this, up and down quarks are generally stable and the most common in the universe, whereas strange, charm, bottom, and top quarks can only be produced in high energy collisions (such as those involving cosmic rays and in particle accelerators).
[src:particle-physics/quark] For every quark flavor there is a corresponding type of antiparticle, known as an **antiquark**, that differs from the quark only in that some of its properties (such as the electric charge) have equal magnitude but opposite sign.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The quark model was independently proposed by physicists Murray Gell-Mann and George Zweig in 1964.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Quarks were introduced as parts of an ordering scheme for hadrons, and there was little evidence for their physical existence until deep inelastic scattering experiments at the Stanford Linear Accelerator Center in 1968.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Accelerator program experiments have provided evidence for all six flavors.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The top quark, first observed at Fermilab in 1995, was the last to be discovered.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The Standard Model is the theoretical framework describing all the known elementary particles.
[src:particle-physics/quark] This model contains six flavors of quarks (q), named up (u), down (d), strange (s), charm (c), bottom (b), and top (t).
[src:particle-physics/quark] Antiparticles of quarks are called *antiquarks*, and are denoted by a bar over the symbol for the corresponding quark, such as u for an up antiquark.
[src:particle-physics/quark] As with antimatter in general, antiquarks have the same mass, mean lifetime, and spin as their respective quarks, but the electric charge and other charges have the opposite sign.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Quarks are spin-⁠1/2⁠ particles, which means they are fermions according to the spin–statistics theorem.
[src:particle-physics/quark] They are subject to the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that no two identical fermions can simultaneously occupy the same quantum state.
[src:particle-physics/quark] This is in contrast to bosons (particles with integer spin), of which any number can be in the same state.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Unlike leptons, quarks possess color charge, which causes them to engage in the strong interaction.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The resulting attraction between different quarks causes the formation of composite particles known as *hadrons* (see *§ Strong interaction and color charge* below).
[src:particle-physics/quark] The quarks that determine the quantum numbers of hadrons are called *valence quarks*; apart from these, any hadron may contain an indefinite number of virtual "sea" quarks, antiquarks, and gluons, which do not influence its quantum numbers.
[src:particle-physics/quark] There are two families of hadrons: baryons, with three valence quarks, and mesons, with a valence quark and an antiquark.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The most common baryons are the proton and the neutron, the building blocks of the atomic nucleus.
[src:particle-physics/quark] A great number of hadrons are known (see list of baryons and list of mesons), most of them differentiated by their quark content and the properties these constituent quarks confer.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The existence of "exotic" hadrons with more valence quarks, such as tetraquarks (qqqq) and pentaquarks (qqqqq), was conjectured from the beginnings of the quark model but not discovered until the early 21st century.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Elementary fermions are grouped into three generations, each comprising two leptons and two quarks.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The first generation includes up and down quarks, the second strange and charm quarks, and the third bottom and top quarks.
[src:particle-physics/quark] All searches for a fourth generation of quarks and other elementary fermions have failed, and there is strong indirect evidence that no more than three generations exist.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Particles in higher generations generally have greater mass and less stability, causing them to decay into lower-generation particles by means of weak interactions.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Only first-generation (up and down) quarks occur commonly in nature.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Studies of heavier quarks are conducted in artificially created conditions, such as in particle accelerators.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Having electric charge, mass, color charge, and flavor, quarks are the only known elementary particles that engage in all four fundamental interactions of contemporary physics: electromagnetism, gravitation, strong interaction, and weak interaction.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Gravitation is too weak to be relevant to individual particle interactions except at extremes of energy (Planck energy) and distance scales (Planck distance).
[src:particle-physics/quark] However, since no successful quantum theory of gravity exists, gravitation is not described by the Standard Model.
[src:particle-physics/quark] See the table of properties below for a more complete overview of the six quark flavors' properties.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The proposal came shortly after Gell-Mann's 1961 formulation of a particle classification system known as the *Eightfold Way*—or, in more technical terms, SU(3) flavor symmetry, streamlining its structure.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Physicist Yuval Ne'eman had independently developed a scheme similar to the Eightfold Way in the same year.
[src:particle-physics/quark] An early attempt at constituent organization was available in the Sakata model.
[src:particle-physics/quark] At the time of the quark theory's inception, the "particle zoo" included a multitude of hadrons, among other particles.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Gell-Mann and Zweig posited that they were not elementary particles, but were instead composed of combinations of quarks and antiquarks.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Their model involved three flavors of quarks, up, down, and strange, to which they ascribed properties such as spin and electric charge.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The initial reaction of the physics community to the proposal was mixed.
[src:particle-physics/quark] There was particular contention about whether the quark was a physical entity or a mere abstraction used to explain concepts that were not fully understood at the time.
[src:particle-physics/quark] In less than a year, extensions to the Gell-Mann–Zweig model were proposed.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Sheldon Glashow and James Bjorken predicted the existence of a fourth flavor of quark, which they called *charm*.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The addition was proposed because it allowed for a better description of the weak interaction (the mechanism that allows quarks to decay), equalized the number of known quarks with the number of known leptons, and implied a mass formula that correctly reproduced the masses of the known mesons.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Deep inelastic scattering experiments conducted in 1968 at the Stanford Linear Accelerator Center (SLAC) and published on October 20, 1969, showed that the proton contained much smaller, point-like objects and was therefore not an elementary particle.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Physicists were reluctant to firmly identify these objects with quarks at the time, instead calling them "partons"—a term coined by Richard Feynman.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The objects that were observed at SLAC would later be identified as up and down quarks as the other flavors were discovered.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Nevertheless, "parton" remains in use as a collective term for the constituents of hadrons (quarks, antiquarks, and gluons).
[src:particle-physics/quark] Richard Taylor, Henry Kendall and Jerome Friedman received the 1990 Nobel Prize in physics for their work at SLAC.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The strange quark's existence was indirectly validated by SLAC's scattering experiments: not only was it a necessary component of Gell-Mann and Zweig's three-quark model, but it provided an explanation for the kaon (K) and pion (π) hadrons discovered in cosmic rays in 1947.
[src:particle-physics/quark] In a 1970 paper, Glashow, John Iliopoulos and Luciano Maiani presented the GIM mechanism (named from their initials) to explain the experimental non-observation of flavor-changing neutral currents.
[src:particle-physics/quark] This theoretical model required the existence of the as-yet undiscovered charm quark.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The number of supposed quark flavors grew to the current six in 1973, when Makoto Kobayashi and Toshihide Maskawa noted that the experimental observation of CP violation could be explained if there were another pair of quarks.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Charm quarks were produced almost simultaneously by two teams in November 1974 (see November Revolution)—one at SLAC under Burton Richter, and one at Brookhaven National Laboratory under Samuel Ting.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The charm quarks were observed bound with charm antiquarks in mesons.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The two parties had assigned the discovered meson two different symbols, J and ψ; thus, it became formally known as the J/ψ meson.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The discovery finally convinced the physics community of the quark model's validity.
[src:particle-physics/quark] In the following years a number of suggestions appeared for extending the quark model to six quarks.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Of these, the 1975 paper by Haim Harari was the first to coin the terms *top* and *bottom* for the additional quarks.
[src:particle-physics/quark] In 1977, the bottom quark was observed by a team at Fermilab led by Leon Lederman.
[src:particle-physics/quark] This was a strong indicator of the top quark's existence: without the top quark, the bottom quark would have been without a partner.
[src:particle-physics/quark] It was not until 1995 that the top quark was finally observed, also by the CDF and DØ teams at Fermilab.
[src:particle-physics/quark] It had a mass much larger than expected, almost as large as that of a gold atom.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The word *quark* is an old English word meaning *to croak* and the above-quoted lines are about a bird choir mocking king Mark of Cornwall in the legend of Tristan and Iseult.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Especially in the German-speaking parts of the world there is a widespread legend, however, that Joyce had taken it from the word *Quark*, a German word of Slavic origin which denotes a curd cheese, but is also a colloquial term for "trivial nonsense".
[src:particle-physics/quark] In the legend it is said that he had heard it on a journey to Germany at a farmers' market in Freiburg.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Some authors, however, defend a possible German origin of Joyce's word *quark*.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Zweig preferred the name *ace* for the particle he had theorized, but Gell-Mann's terminology came to prominence once the quark model had been commonly accepted.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The quark flavors were given their names for several reasons.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The up and down quarks are named after the up and down components of isospin, which they carry.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Strange quarks were given their name because they were discovered to be components of the strange particles discovered in cosmic rays years before the quark model was proposed; these particles were deemed "strange" because they had unusually long lifetimes.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Alternative names for top and bottom quarks are "truth" and "beauty", but these names have somewhat fallen out of use.
[src:particle-physics/quark] While "truth" never did catch on, accelerator complexes devoted to massive production of bottom quarks are sometimes called "beauty factories".
[src:particle-physics/quark] Quarks have fractional electric charge values, either −⁠1/3⁠, or +⁠2/3⁠ times the elementary charge (*e*), depending on flavor.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Up, charm, and top quarks (collectively referred to as *up-type quarks*) have a charge of +⁠2/3⁠ *e*; down, strange, and bottom quarks (*down-type quarks*) have a charge of −⁠1/3⁠ *e*.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Antiquarks have the opposite charge to their corresponding quarks; up-type antiquarks have charges of −⁠2/3⁠ *e* and down-type antiquarks have charges of +⁠1/3⁠ *e*.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Since the electric charge of a hadron is the sum of the charges of the constituent quarks, all hadrons have integer charges: the combination of three quarks (baryons), three antiquarks (antibaryons), or a quark and an antiquark (mesons) always results in integer charges.
[src:particle-physics/quark] For example, the hadron constituents of atomic nuclei, neutrons and protons, have charges of 0 *e* and +1 *e*, respectively; the neutron is composed of two down quarks and one up quark, and the proton of two up quarks and one down quark.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Spin is an intrinsic property of elementary particles, and its direction is an important degree of freedom.
[src:particle-physics/quark] It is sometimes visualized as the rotation of an object around its own axis (hence the name "spin"), though this notion is somewhat misguided at subatomic scales because elementary particles are believed to be point-like.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Spin can be represented by a vector whose length is measured in units of the reduced Planck constant *ħ* (pronounced "h bar").
[src:particle-physics/quark] For quarks, a measurement of the spin vector component along any axis can only yield the values +⁠*ħ*/2⁠ or −⁠*ħ*/2⁠; for this reason quarks are classified as spin-⁠1/2⁠ particles.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The component of spin along a given axis—by convention the *z* axis—is often denoted by an up arrow ↑ for the value +⁠1/2⁠ and a down arrow ↓ for the value −⁠1/2⁠, placed after the symbol for flavor.
[src:particle-physics/quark] For example, an up quark with a spin of +⁠1/2⁠ along the *z* axis is denoted by u↑.
[src:particle-physics/quark] A quark of one flavor can transform into a quark of another flavor only through the weak interaction, one of the four fundamental interactions in particle physics.
[src:particle-physics/quark] By absorbing or emitting a W boson, any up-type quark (up, charm, and top quarks) can change into any down-type quark (down, strange, and bottom quarks) and vice versa.
[src:particle-physics/quark] This flavor transformation mechanism causes the radioactive process of beta decay, in which a neutron (n) "splits" into a proton (p), an electron (e− ) and an electron antineutrino (ν e) (see picture).
[src:particle-physics/quark] This occurs when one of the down quarks in the neutron (udd) decays into an up quark by emitting a virtual W− boson, transforming the neutron into a proton (uud).
[src:particle-physics/quark] The W− boson then decays into an electron and an electron antineutrino.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Both beta decay and the inverse process of *inverse beta decay* are routinely used in medical applications such as positron emission tomography (PET) and in experiments involving neutrino detection.
[src:particle-physics/quark] While the process of flavor transformation is the same for all quarks, each quark has a preference to transform into the quark of its own generation.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The relative tendencies of all flavor transformations are described by a mathematical table, called the Cabibbo–Kobayashi–Maskawa matrix (CKM matrix).
[src:particle-physics/quark] where *V**ij* represents the tendency of a quark of flavor *i* to change into a quark of flavor *j* (or vice versa).
[src:particle-physics/quark] There exists an equivalent weak interaction matrix for leptons (right side of the W boson on the above beta decay diagram), called the Pontecorvo–Maki–Nakagawa–Sakata matrix (PMNS matrix).
[src:particle-physics/quark] Together, the CKM and PMNS matrices describe all flavor transformations, but the links between the two are not yet clear.
[src:particle-physics/quark] According to quantum chromodynamics (QCD), quarks possess a property called *color charge*.
[src:particle-physics/quark] There are three types of color charge, arbitrarily labeled *blue*, *green*, and *red*.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Each of them is complemented by an anticolor—*antiblue*, *antigreen*, and *antired*.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Every quark carries a color, while every antiquark carries an anticolor.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The system of attraction and repulsion between quarks charged with different combinations of the three colors is called strong interaction, which is mediated by force carrying particles known as *gluons*; this is discussed at length below.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The theory that describes strong interactions is called quantum chromodynamics (QCD).
[src:particle-physics/quark] A quark, which will have a single color value, can form a bound system with an antiquark carrying the corresponding anticolor.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The result of two attracting quarks will be color neutrality: a quark with color charge *ξ* plus an antiquark with color charge −*ξ* will result in a color charge of 0 (or "white" color) and the formation of a meson.
[src:particle-physics/quark] This is analogous to the additive color model in basic optics.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Similarly, the combination of three quarks, each with different color charges, or three antiquarks, each with different anticolor charges, will result in the same "white" color charge and the formation of a baryon or antibaryon.
[src:particle-physics/quark] In modern particle physics, gauge symmetries—a kind of symmetry group—relate interactions between particles (see gauge theories).
[src:particle-physics/quark] Color SU(3) (commonly abbreviated to SU(3)c) is the gauge symmetry that relates the color charge in quarks and is the defining symmetry for quantum chromodynamics.
[src:particle-physics/quark] SU(3)c color transformations correspond to "rotations" in color space (which, mathematically speaking, is a complex space).
[src:particle-physics/quark] Every quark flavor *f*, each with subtypes *f*B, *f*G, *f*R corresponding to the quark colors, forms a triplet: a three-component quantum field that transforms under the fundamental representation of SU(3)c.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The requirement that SU(3)c should be local—that is, that its transformations be allowed to vary with space and time—determines the properties of the strong interaction.
[src:particle-physics/quark] In particular, it implies the existence of eight gluon types to act as its force carriers.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Two terms are used in referring to a quark's mass: *current quark mass* refers to the mass of a quark by itself, while *constituent quark mass* refers to the current quark mass plus the mass of the gluon particle field surrounding the quark.
[src:particle-physics/quark] These masses typically have very different values.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Most of a hadron's mass comes from the gluons that bind the constituent quarks together, rather than from the quarks themselves.
[src:particle-physics/quark] While gluons are inherently massless, they possess energy—more specifically, quantum chromodynamics binding energy (QCBE)—and it is this that contributes so greatly to the overall mass of the hadron (see mass in special relativity).
[src:particle-physics/quark] For example, a proton has a mass of approximately 938 MeV/*c*2, of which the rest mass of its three valence quarks only contributes about 9 MeV/*c*2; much of the remainder can be attributed to the field energy of the gluons (see chiral symmetry breaking).
[src:particle-physics/quark] The Standard Model posits that elementary particles derive their masses from the Higgs mechanism, which is associated to the Higgs boson.
[src:particle-physics/quark] It is hoped that further research into the reasons for the top quark's large mass of ~173 GeV/*c*2, almost the mass of a gold atom, might reveal more about the origin of the mass of quarks and other elementary particles.
[src:particle-physics/quark] In QCD, quarks are considered to be point-like entities, with no structure.
[src:particle-physics/quark] As of 2014, experimental evidence indicates they have no structure greater than 10−4 times the size of a proton, i.e. less than 10−19 m.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The following table summarizes the key properties of the six quarks.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Flavor quantum numbers (isospin (*I*3), charm (*C*), strangeness (*S*, not to be confused with spin), topness (*T*), and bottomness (*B*′)) are assigned to certain quark flavors, and denote qualities of quark-based systems and hadrons.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The baryon number (*B*) is +⁠1/3⁠ for all quarks, as baryons are made of three quarks.
[src:particle-physics/quark] For antiquarks, the electric charge (*Q*) and all flavor quantum numbers (*B*, *I*3, *C*, *S*, *T*, and *B*′) are of opposite sign.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Mass and total angular momentum (*J*; equal to spin for point particles) do not change sign for the antiquarks.
[src:particle-physics/quark] As described by quantum chromodynamics, the strong interaction between quarks is mediated by gluons, massless vector gauge bosons.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Each gluon carries one color charge and one anticolor charge.
[src:particle-physics/quark] In the standard framework of particle interactions (part of a more general formulation known as perturbation theory), gluons are constantly exchanged between quarks through a virtual emission and absorption process.
[src:particle-physics/quark] When a gluon is transferred between quarks, a color change occurs in both; for example, if a red quark emits a red–antigreen gluon, it becomes green, and if a green quark absorbs a red–antigreen gluon, it becomes red.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Therefore, while each quark's color constantly changes, their strong interaction is preserved.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Since gluons carry color charge, they themselves are able to emit and absorb other gluons.
[src:particle-physics/quark] This causes *asymptotic freedom*: as quarks come closer to each other, the chromodynamic binding force between them weakens.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Conversely, as the distance between quarks increases, the binding force strengthens.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The color field becomes stressed, much as an elastic band is stressed when stretched, and more gluons of appropriate color are spontaneously created to strengthen the field.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Above a certain energy threshold, pairs of quarks and antiquarks are created.
[src:particle-physics/quark] These pairs bind with the quarks being separated, causing new hadrons to form.
[src:particle-physics/quark] This phenomenon is known as *color confinement*: quarks never appear in isolation.
[src:particle-physics/quark] This process of hadronization occurs before quarks formed in a high energy collision are able to interact in any other way.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The only exception is the top quark, which may decay before it hadronizes.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Hadrons contain, along with the *valence quarks* (q v) that contribute to their quantum numbers, virtual quark–antiquark (qq) pairs known as *sea quarks* (q s).
[src:particle-physics/quark] Sea quarks form when a gluon of the hadron's color field splits; this process also works in reverse in that the annihilation of two sea quarks produces a gluon.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The result is a constant flux of gluon splits and creations colloquially known as "the sea".
[src:particle-physics/quark] Sea quarks are much less stable than their valence counterparts, and they typically annihilate each other within the interior of the hadron.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Despite this, sea quarks can hadronize into baryonic or mesonic particles under certain circumstances.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Under sufficiently extreme conditions, quarks may become "deconfined" out of bound states and propagate as thermalized "free" excitations in the larger medium.
[src:particle-physics/quark] In the course of asymptotic freedom, the strong interaction becomes weaker at increasing temperatures.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Eventually, color confinement would be effectively lost in an extremely hot plasma of freely moving quarks and gluons.
[src:particle-physics/quark] This theoretical phase of matter is called quark–gluon plasma.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The exact conditions needed to give rise to this state are unknown and have been the subject of a great deal of speculation and experimentation.
[src:particle-physics/quark] An estimate puts the needed temperature at (1.90±0.02)×1012 kelvin.
[src:particle-physics/quark] While a state of entirely free quarks and gluons has never been achieved (despite numerous attempts by CERN in the 1980s and 1990s), recent experiments at the Relativistic Heavy Ion Collider have yielded evidence for liquid-like quark matter exhibiting "nearly perfect" fluid motion.
[src:particle-physics/quark] The quark–gluon plasma would be characterized by a great increase in the number of heavier quark pairs in relation to the number of up and down quark pairs.
[src:particle-physics/quark] It is believed that in the period prior to 10−6 seconds after the Big Bang (the quark epoch), the universe was filled with quark–gluon plasma, as the temperature was too high for hadrons to be stable.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Given sufficiently high baryon densities and relatively low temperatures—possibly comparable to those found in neutron stars—quark matter is expected to degenerate into a Fermi liquid of weakly interacting quarks.
[src:particle-physics/quark] This liquid would be characterized by a condensation of colored quark Cooper pairs, thereby breaking the local SU(3)c symmetry.
[src:particle-physics/quark] Because quark Cooper pairs harbor color charge, such a phase of quark matter would be color superconductive; that is, color charge would be able to pass through it with no resistance.
